<l n="d">yasyāsaṁkhya-ripu-pratāpa-jayinā doṣṇā mr̥gendrāyitaṁ||</l>
</lg>
<lg n="2" met="āryā">
<l n="ab">sakalaḥ kalaṅka-rahitaḥ <lb
n="2"/>kṣata-timiras toyadheḥ śaśāṅka Iva|</l><!--
L2. Fleet prints timira-toyadheḥ, which is unmetrical. M's timiras is metrically correct and makes better sense.
-->
<l n="cd">tasmād udapādi suto devaḥ śrī-harṣagupta Iti||</l>
</lg>
<lg n="3" met="sragdharā">
<l n="a">yo yogyā-kāla-helāvanata-dr̥ḍha-dhanur-bhīma-<sic>v</sic>āṇaugha-pātī</l><!--
L2. Fleet translates "(his) firm bow that was bent with ease at the befitting proper time", but yogyā (f) exercise, gymnastics, drill. He is probably also wrong about the bit with Lakṣmī, but this needs consideration, and the reading seems doubtful too. [There seem to be plenty more problems with Fleet's translation and I'm not checking it systematically.]
-->
